          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
          Kurdish future in the air
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/kurdish-group-nears-end-mission-turkey-conflict.png" alt="The Kurdish militant group said it was close to completing its historic mission after decades of conflict with Turkey" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i> The Kurdish militant group said it was "close to completing its historic mission" after decades of conflict with Turkey. Credits: NAZEER AL-KHATIB/AFP via Getty Images</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Following imprisoned leader Abdullah Ocalan‚Äôs call for a permanent ceasefire, the Kurdish Workers‚Äô Party (PKK) has decided to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-may-25-spotlight-h1-1-disband-and-end-its-armed-struggle" target="_blank">disband and end its armed struggle</a>. In their 12th Congress summit, the PKK said it wants to resolve the Kurdish issue through democratic politics.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         The disbanding comes amid ongoing <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-may-25-spotlight-h1-2-turkish-military-pressure" target="_blank">Turkish military pressure</a> and changing regional dynamics. If the PKK fully dissolves, it could signal a renewed phase in Turkish-Kurdish relations and afford them some privileges through negotiation. Turkey's governing party welcomed the announcement "as a significant step toward the goal of a Turkey without terror."</p>  
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         The PKK was founded in 1978 with the aim of an independent Kurdish state. It eventually transitioned to pursuing autonomy within Turkey. Armed clashes, bombings, and military crackdowns led to international communities labeling the PKK as a terrorist group. However, there has been considerable debate over the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-may-25-spotlight-h1-3-fairness-of-this-designation" target="_blank">fairness of this designation</a>.</p>  
        </mj-text>
