      <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
        The Indo-Pacific turnaround
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>Summary: The Indo-Pacific construct preserves the old order, but also offers a framework for re-conceptualizing multipolar geopolitics. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The Indo-Pacific concept was developed as a response to the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-may-25-analysis-h1-7-decline-of-us-unipolarity" target="_blank">decline of US unipolarity</a> in the 21st century. After the Cold War, the US was a leader in foreign policy, promoting globalization, democracy, and open markets. However, their supremacy tanked because of the 2008 financial crisis. Meanwhile, China's rapid growth exposed flaws in the US-led system.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The shift from the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-may-25-analysis-h1-8-asia-pacific-concept" target="_blank">Asia-Pacific concept</a> aims to counterbalance China. The newer framework surrounds China with security and economic partnerships such as <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-may-25-analysis-h1-9-aukus" target="_blank">AUKUS</a> and the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-may-25-analysis-h1-10-quad" target="_blank">Quad</a>,  placing India as a competing regional power. While it promotes an inclusive order, the Indo-Pacific also serves US strategic goals. They also try to counteract the rise of China‚Äôs Belt and Road Initiative (BRI).</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Meanwhile, China is building cooperation with Tibet and Pakistan and developing corridors across Central Asia. China‚Äôs global domination idea involves regionalism based on economic cooperation and sovereignty rather than a "values-based system" of the US. Their BRI, partnerships with ASEAN, and bilateral relationships exemplify this approach.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       Indo-Pacific forces us to consider a different approach to great power rivalries. It undermines the Cold War picture of two cohesive blocs and rather presents a network of overlapping institutions and agreements, each serving specific functional needs while collectively contributing to regional stability. It has also given us a potential blueprint for how future global governance may be structured in a multipolar world centered on Asia.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
