          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
         How did the Hague become a center for international law?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/hague-international-city-peace-justice-growth.png" alt="As Hague‚Äôs reputation as the International City of Peace and Justice grows, The Hague continues to attract more and more international organizations" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>As Hague‚Äôs reputation as the International City of Peace and Justice grows, The Hague continues to attract more and more international organizations. Credits: SDA</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        The Hague became a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-may-25-foundations-h1-17-hub-for-international-law" target="_blank">hub for international law</a> because of its early efforts to promote peace and justice. The Dutch legacy of neutrality at the turn of the 20th century and its active international engagement helped them to facilitate the transition.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       Two defining events that helped put the Hague on the international map were the First and Second <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-may-25-foundations-h1-18-hague-peace-conferences" target="_blank">Hague Peace Conferences</a> in 1899 and 1907. These events led to the creation of the Permanent Court of Arbitration and the Peace Palace.</p>
       <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       In 1922, the Permanent Court of International Justice was established in The Hague under the League of Nations. This court was later replaced by the International Court of Justice (ICJ) in 1945, which serves as the main judicial body for the United Nations. Currently, it is also home to the International Criminal Court (ICC), which prosecutes individuals for crimes like genocide, war crimes, crimes against humanity, and aggression. </p>
       <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       The Hague is home to 180 nationalities and 500 international organizations, which help the city solidify its reputation as the world‚Äôs judicial capital.</p>
       </mj-text>
